response:
The function f(x) = |log₂x - 1| can be represented as a piecewise function:

$$
f(x) = \begin{cases}
1 - \log_{2}x & \text{if } 0 < x \leq 2 \\
\log_{2}x - 1 & \text{if } x > 2
\end{cases}
$$

For the case when $0 < x \leq 2$, the equation f(x) = k becomes 1 - log₂x = k. Solving for x₁, we get:
$$
\begin{align*}
1 - \log_{2}x_1 &= k \\
\log_{2}x_1 &= 1 - k \\
x_1 &= 2^{(1 - k)}
\end{align*}
$$

For the case when $x > 2$, the equation f(x) = k becomes log₂x - 1 = k. Solving for x₂, we get:
$$
\begin{align*}
\log_{2}x_2 - 1 &= k \\
\log_{2}x_2 &= 1 + k \\
x_2 &= 2^{(1 + k)}
\end{align*}
$$

Now, we find the product of x₁ and x₂:
$$
\begin{align*}
x_1 \cdot x_2 &= 2^{(1 - k)} \cdot 2^{(1 + k)} \\
&= 2^{(1 - k + 1 + k)} \\
&= 2^{2} \\
&= \boxed{4}
\end{align*}
$$

Thus, the answer is C.

